In the intricate and often demanding mathematical domain of [functional analysis](/Functional_analysis), a "state" of an [operator system](/Operator_system) is precisely defined as a [positive linear functional](/Positive_linear_functional) that possesses a [norm](/Operator_norm) of exactly 1. One might imagine it as a normalized measurement, a fundamental building block in understanding the structure of these abstract systems. These states in [functional analysis](/Functional_analysis) serve as profound [generalizations](/Generalization) of the concept of [density matrices](/Density_matrix) found within [quantum mechanics](/Quantum_mechanics), which themselves are the mathematical representations of [quantum states](/Quantum_state). This includes both the composite and often enigmatic [mixed states](/Quantum_state) and the more fundamental, irreducible [pure states](/Quantum_state). Furthermore, [density matrices](/Density_matrix) extend the idea of mere [state vectors](/Quantum_state), which are capable of representing only [pure states](/Quantum_state) and often fall short when describing the more complex statistical ensembles inherent in quantum systems.

Consider an operator system M, which resides within a larger [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra) A that is equipped with an identity element. The collection of all possible states of M, frequently denoted by S(M), exhibits several crucial topological and geometric properties. This set is inherently [convex](/Convex_set), meaning that for any two states within S(M), any convex combination of them (a weighted average with non-negative weights summing to one) will also be a state. Moreover, S(M) is [weak-\* closed](/Weak_topology) within the [Banach dual space](/Dual_space) M\*. The confluence of these properties—convexity and weak-\* closedness—is not merely an academic curiosity; it implies, by the profound [Banach–Alaoglu theorem](/Banach%E2%80%93Alaoglu_theorem), that the set of all states of M, when endowed with the [weak-\* topology](/Weak_topology), forms a [compact Hausdorff space](/Compact_space). This meticulously structured topological space is formally recognized as the state space of M.

In the elegant and rigorous [C*-algebraic formulation of quantum mechanics](/C*-algebraic_quantum_mechanics), states, as defined above in the context of [functional analysis](/Functional_analysis), directly correspond to the physical states of a quantum system. They serve as the mathematical machinery for mapping physical [observables](/Observable) (which are represented by the [self-adjoint elements](/Self-adjoint_operator) within the [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra)) to their expected measurement outcomes, which are, reassuringly, real numbers. This bridge between abstract mathematics and physical reality underscores the fundamental importance of understanding these "states."

### Jordan decomposition

One might consider states as sophisticated, noncommutative [generalizations](/Generalization) of [probability measures](/Probability_measure). This isn't just a casual analogy; it's a deep structural parallel. When one encounters a commutative [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra) A, the renowned [Gelfand representation](/Gelfand_representation) theorem dictates that A is always isomorphic to the algebra C₀(X) of continuous functions vanishing at infinity on some [locally compact Hausdorff space](/Locally_compact_space) X. In this specific, more tractable commutative scenario, the state space S(A) elegantly transforms into the set of positive [Radon measures](/Radon_measure) on X. Furthermore, the [pure states](/Quantum_state) within S(A) are then simply the [evaluation functionals](/Evaluation_map) at points in X, effectively picking out specific "points" in the underlying space.

More generally, and perhaps more profoundly, the [Gelfand–Naimark–Segal (GNS) construction](/GNS_construction) reveals a fundamental truth: every state, regardless of its initial abstract form, can be realized as a [vector state](/Vector_state) after selecting an appropriate [representation](/Representation_theory) of the [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra). It's as if every abstract state eventually finds its concrete manifestation as a vector in some [Hilbert space](/Hilbert_space).

A [bounded linear functional](/Bounded_operator) on a [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra) A is designated as self-adjoint if its application to the [self-adjoint elements](/Self-adjoint_operator) of A consistently yields real-valued outcomes. These self-adjoint functionals are, in essence, the noncommutative counterparts to [signed measures](/Signed_measure), introducing the possibility of "negative probabilities" in a generalized sense, though their interpretation requires careful consideration.

The classical [Jordan decomposition](/Hahn_decomposition_theorem) theorem in [measure theory](/Measure_theory) asserts that any [signed measure](/Signed_measure) can be uniquely expressed as the difference of two positive measures whose supports are disjoint. This elegant decomposition, a cornerstone of measure theory, possesses a powerful and equally elegant extension into the noncommutative landscape of [functional analysis](/Functional_analysis).

**Theorem** — Every self-adjoint

$f$

in

$A^{*}$

can be written as

$f=f_{+}-f_{-}$

where

$f_{+}$

and

$f_{-}$

are positive functionals and

$\Vert f\Vert =\Vert f_{+}\Vert +\Vert f_{-}\Vert$

.

This theorem ensures that even in the more abstract and complex setting of [C*-algebras](/C*-algebra), the fundamental idea of decomposing a "signed" quantity into its positive and negative components remains valid, providing a crucial analytical tool.

#### Proof

A proof of this theorem, while requiring a careful step-by-step approach, can be conceptually sketched as follows, revealing the interplay of various foundational theorems in [functional analysis](/Functional_analysis):

1.  Let $\Omega$ be defined as the [weak-\* compact](/Weak_topology) set comprising all positive linear functionals on $A$ whose norm is less than or equal to 1. The compactness of $\Omega$ is a direct consequence of the [Banach–Alaoglu theorem](/Banach%E2%80%93Alaoglu_theorem), which guarantees the weak-\* compactness of the unit ball in the dual space. Let $C(\Omega)$ denote the space of continuous complex-valued functions defined on this compact Hausdorff space $\Omega$.

2.  Through a fundamental result known as [Kadison's function representation](/Richard_V._Kadison), the [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra) $A$ can be viewed as a closed linear subspace embedded within $C(\Omega)$. This representation provides a way to "linearize" or "abelianize" the algebra $A$ for certain analytical purposes, allowing the application of techniques from commutative analysis.

3.  Given the self-adjoint functional $f$ on $A$, the powerful [Hahn–Banach theorem](/Hahn%E2%80%93Banach_theorem) comes into play. This theorem guarantees that $f$ can be extended to a functional $g$ defined on the entire space $C(\Omega)^{\ast}$ (the dual space of $C(\Omega)$), crucially maintaining its norm: $\Vert g\Vert =\Vert f\Vert$. This extension is essential as it allows us to work with a functional on a more "well-behaved" space.

4.  Leveraging the classical [Riesz representation theorem](/Riesz_representation_theorem) from measure theory, which establishes an isometric isomorphism between the dual of $C(X)$ (for a compact Hausdorff space $X$) and the space of [Radon measures](/Radon_measure) on $X$, one can express $g$ as an integral:

    $g(\cdot )=\int \cdot \;d\mu$

    Here, $\mu$ is a [Radon measure](/Radon_measure) on $\Omega$. Due to the initial self-adjointness of $f$ (and thus $g$), the measure $\mu$ can be chosen to be a [signed measure](/Signed_measure) with real values.

5.  Now, the classical [Jordan decomposition](/Hahn_decomposition_theorem) for [signed measures](/Signed_measure) is applied. This allows us to uniquely decompose $\mu$ into the difference of two positive measures:

    $\mu =\mu _{+}-\mu _{-}$

    where $\mu_{+}$ and $\mu_{-}$ are positive [Radon measures](/Radon_measure) on $\Omega$.

6.  Finally, by restricting the functionals associated with these positive measures, specifically $\textstyle \int \cdot \;d\mu _{+}$ and $\textstyle \int \cdot \;d\mu _{-}$, back to the original [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra) $A$, we obtain the desired positive functionals $f_{+}$ and $f_{-}$. These restricted functionals fulfill all the properties stipulated by the theorem, thereby completing the proof.

This elegant decomposition implies a profound structural consequence: the entire dual space $A^{\ast}$ of a [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra) is, in fact, the linear span of its states. This means that any continuous linear functional on $A$ can be expressed as a linear combination of states, underscoring the fundamental role states play in characterizing the linear structure of the dual space. It’s a bit like saying all complex phenomena can be broken down into elementary measurements.

### Some important classes of states

Not all states are created equal, and discerning their various categories is crucial for deeper analysis. Each class offers unique insights into the structure and properties of the underlying [operator system](/Operator_system) or [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra).

#### Pure states

The [Krein-Milman theorem](/Krein-Milman_theorem), a cornerstone of [convex analysis](/Convex_analysis), asserts that any compact convex set in a [locally convex topological vector space](/Locally_convex_topological_vector_space) is the closed convex hull of its [extreme points](/Extreme_point). Applied to the state space of M, this theorem guarantees the existence of such [extreme points](/Extreme_point). These unique, irreducible [extreme points](/Extreme_point) of the state space are precisely what we term **pure states**. Any state that is not pure is referred to as a **mixed state**, which can always be expressed as a convex combination (a statistical mixture) of pure states. In a quantum mechanical context, pure states represent definite, maximally specified quantum configurations, while mixed states represent statistical ensembles of such configurations.

#### Vector states

When working with a [Hilbert space](/Hilbert_space) H and a specific unit vector $x$ within H (meaning $||x||=1$), one can naturally construct a [positive linear functional](/Positive_linear_functional) on the algebra of [bounded operators](/Bounded_operator) B(H) acting on H. This is defined by the formula $\omega_x(T) := \langle Tx, x \rangle$ for any operator $T$ in B(H). The inner product $\langle \cdot, \cdot \rangle$ ensures the positivity, and the unit norm of $x$ ensures that $\omega_x(1) = ||x||^2 = 1$, thus making it a state. If $A$ is a [C*-subalgebra](/C*-algebra) of B(H) and M is an [operator system](/Operator_system) contained within $A$, then the restriction of $\omega_x$ to M will also define a [positive linear functional](/Positive_linear_functional) on M. States of M that originate in this manner, directly from unit vectors in a [Hilbert space](/Hilbert_space) H, are aptly named **vector states** of M. They are the most concrete realization of states, directly tied to the fundamental elements of [Hilbert space](/Hilbert_space) theory.

#### Faithful states

A state $\tau$ on a [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra) $A$ is considered **faithful** if it possesses a particular property that speaks to its ability to "detect" non-zero elements. Specifically, $\tau(a^{*}a) = 0$ implies that $a = 0$ for any element $a \in A$. This condition means that if the state assigns a "zero expectation value" to the positive element $a^{*}a$ (which is always positive semi-definite), then the element $a$ itself must be zero. In essence, a faithful state is one that doesn't "lose" information about the non-zero nature of elements, providing a strong link between the algebraic structure and the functional's values.

#### Normal states

The concept of a **normal state** $\tau$ is critical for understanding continuity properties with respect to operator convergence. A state $\tau$ is defined as normal if, for every monotone, increasing [net](/Net_(mathematics)) $H_{\alpha}$ of operators that possesses a least upper bound $H$ (in the sense of the operator order), the net of functional values $\tau(H_{\alpha})$ converges to $\tau(H)$. This property essentially ensures that the state respects certain types of limits of operators, making it well-behaved under sequential or net-based convergence. This is a powerful condition, often linking states to representations on [Hilbert spaces](/Hilbert_space) where such continuity is more explicit.

#### Tracial states

A **tracial state** $\tau$ is a state that satisfies a particular commutative property, even in a noncommutative algebra. Specifically, it must satisfy $\tau(AB) = \tau(BA)$ for all elements $A$ and $B$ in the algebra. This property, reminiscent of the trace function on matrices, implies a certain "cyclic invariance" under multiplication. For any [separable C*-algebra](/Separable_space), the set of all tracial states forms a [Choquet simplex](/Choquet_theory), which is a specific type of convex set whose geometry is particularly well-understood and allows for unique integral representations of its points. This geometric structure provides deep insights into the behavior of tracial states.

#### Factorial states

A **factorial state** of a [C*-algebra](/C*-algebra) $A$ is a state distinguished by the nature of the [von Neumann algebra](/Von_Neumann_algebra) generated by its corresponding [GNS representation](/GNS_construction). More precisely, it is a state for which the [commutant](/Commutant) of the image of $A$ under the [GNS representation](/GNS_construction) is a [factor](/Von_Neumann_algebra). A [factor](/Von_Neumann_algebra) is a [von Neumann algebra](/Von_Neumann_algebra) whose center consists only of scalar multiples of the identity operator. This condition implies that the representation is "as irreducible as possible" in a certain sense, lacking any nontrivial central elements that would decompose the representation further. Factorial states are therefore crucial in the classification of [von Neumann algebras](/Von_Neumann_algebra) and the study of fundamental structures in [operator theory](/Operator_theory).

